Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma asked the congregation to pray for the ANC so that candidates who don&#8217;t win at December conference accept defeat. PIETERMARITZBURG - African National Congress (ANC) NEC member Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma has asked religious leaders in Pietermaritzburg to pray for peace in the party in the lead up to the elective conference in December.Dlamini-Zuma was speaking at a prayer session on Friday afternoon.The former African Union chair has been formally welcomed back home by the region after her tenure in Ethiopia.Religious leaders there have been praying against social ills in KwaZulu-Natal, a looming economic meltdown and political killings in the province.Speaking in isizulu, Dlamini-Zuma asked the congregation to pray that as the ANC prepares for its elective conference in December that candidates who don t win accept their defeat and work together with the new leadership.She has called for the respect for those chosen in order to uphold peace and stability in the ruling party.She says the ANC cannot be further divided after December, as this will only weaken the party s ability to fight against opposition.(Edited by Winnie Theletsane)